---

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the linguine.

Zest and halve the @lemon{1}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(chopped, stalks and all).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @linguine{180} and bring back to the boil. Cook
until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, reserve the @reserved pasta water{100%ml} for the sauce, then drain in a
#colander{}.

Pop the linguine back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it from
sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the shallot and cook, stirring frequently, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the reserved pasta water and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, stir together, then
bring to the boil. Simmer for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @king prawns{150%g} and @peas{120%g} into the sauce and cook for another
~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are
> cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, stir the @creme fraiche{75%g} and lemon zest into the sauce.
Bring back to the boil, then remove from the heat.

Season with @ground black pepper{}, then stir through the cooked pasta and half the
parsley.

Add a squeeze of lemon juice. Taste and season with salt, pepper and more lemon juice if
needed.

When ready, share the prawn linguine between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle with the remaining parsley, then serve with any remaining lemon cut into wedges
for squeezing over. Enjoy!